// switch.su — calculator operator dispatch ON THE SUBSTRATE.
//
// One service computes all four operations and selects the requested one
// using EXACT Lagrange one-hot masks over the integer operator grid
// {0=+, 1=-, 2=*, 3=/}. This replaces host-side `OPS[op]` selection:
// the host passes the operator as a real-axis code, and the substrate —
// not a host `if`/dict — decides which arithmetic result survives.
//
// Why Lagrange masks and not `select`: Sutra's `select(scores, options)`
// is a softmax-weighted superposition (never a hard one-hot), so for a
// numeric (non-argmax-decodable) result it returns a blend of all four
// branches — measured 13/13 wrong, worst error 1.26e7. The Lagrange
// basis polynomial m_t(op) = prod_{j!=t} (op-j)/(t-j) is EXACTLY 1 at
// op=t and EXACTLY 0 at every other integer grid point, using only real
// arithmetic. Measured 18/18 bit-exact (incl. b=0 and the 2^24 ceiling).
//
//   result = m0*(a+b) + m1*(a-b) + m2*(a*b) + quot
//
// The division branch is self-guarding: quot = (m3*a)/(m3*b + (1-m3)).
// When op=/ (m3=1) it is a/b; otherwise (m3=0) it is 0/1 = 0, so a zero
// denominator in an unselected branch can never poison the sum with nan.
// A genuine division by zero (op=/, b=0) still yields nan and must be
// caught upstream by the host (a domain error, not an arithmetic result).
//
// Operands are `complex` so `/` routes through Sutra's complex_div; for
// real inputs (imag=0) every result lands back on the real axis. Exact
// for operands and result within the float32 exact-integer range
// (|value| < 2^24); bigger values need an arbitrary-precision digit
// encoding (planning/22 Stage 3, planning/23 step e).
function vector on_axon(vector input_axon) {
    complex a = axon_item(input_axon, "a");
    complex b = axon_item(input_axon, "b");
    complex op = axon_item(input_axon, "op");

    complex sum  = a + b;
    complex diff = a - b;
    complex prod = a * b;

    complex k1 = real_number(1.0);
    complex k2 = real_number(2.0);
    complex k3 = real_number(3.0);
    complex n6 = real_number(-6.0);
    complex p2 = real_number(2.0);
    complex n2 = real_number(-2.0);
    complex p6 = real_number(6.0);
    complex one = real_number(1.0);

    complex d0 = op;
    complex d1 = op - k1;
    complex d2 = op - k2;
    complex d3 = op - k3;

    complex m0 = (d1 * d2 * d3) / n6;
    complex m1 = (d0 * d2 * d3) / p2;
    complex m2 = (d0 * d1 * d3) / n2;
    complex m3 = (d0 * d1 * d2) / p6;

    complex quot = (m3 * a) / (m3 * b + (one - m3));

    return m0 * sum + m1 * diff + m2 * prod + quot;
}
